Rasch Analysis

  • Rasch analysis is a modern test theory approach.

  • Rasch is a probabilistic approach to measurement: the probability of a response is a function of the ability of the respondent and the difficulty of the item.

  • The Rasch analysis tests if the responses to the questions also called items follow an expected pattern, called the Guttmann pattern.

  • In Rasch analysis a series of assumptions are tested. If the data does not conform, than the data is adjusted (and not the model) to conform to the expectations of an instrument with metric properties.

Guttman Pattern

The probability of a correct response is a function of the person’s ability. Imagine a dataset with scale responses to ten items (I1 to I10), where the item response can be 0 or 1 (0, being for example wrong (red cross) and 1 correct). And ten persons (J1 to J10) having responded to the questionnaire. Each row contains the responses of a person. Each column contains the responses to one item.

If the marginal scores, items and person, are sorted the Guttman pattern shows:

  • the smaller the item score, the more difficult the item.

  • the greater the person score, the more proficient the person.

  • most persons with same total score are expected to show the same response pattern. For example: most persons with score of 5, should have responded the 5 easiest items correctly.

  • However, beyond theory, data with perfect Guttman pattern is unlikely.

General Rasch Equation

Dichotomous Rasch Model (Rasch 1960) is used when item responses can be scored 0 or 1, i.e. when each item of a scale has only two response options.

The probability of an correct response \(x=1\) for a person \(j\), on a particular item \(i\) is written as a function of the \(i^{th}\) item difficulty \(\beta\) and the \(j^{th}\) person’s ability \(\theta\):

\[P(X_{ij} =1 | \theta_j) = \frac{exp(\theta_j - \beta_i)} {1 + exp(\theta_j - \beta_i)}\]

For random events with two outcomes (e.g. “success” or “failure”), the probability of “success” is formalized as \(p\) and the probability of “failure” as \(q = 1-p\). For the Rasch model, the probability of the response \(x =0\), as alternative to \(x = 1\) is then

\[P(X_{ij}=0) = 1 - \frac{exp(\theta_j - \beta_i)} {1 + exp(\theta_j - \beta_i)} = \frac{1} {1 + exp (\theta_j - \beta_i)}\]

For example: the probability that a person with a proficiency of \(\theta = 5\) responds correctly to an item with difficulty \(\beta = 6\) is

\[P(X_{ij}=1) = \frac{e^{5 - 6}} {1 + e^{5 - 6}} = \frac{e^{-1}} {1 + e^{-1}} = 0.27\]

  • What is the probability that the person responds \(X=0\)?
  • What happens if the person’s ability equals the item difficulty?

Family of Rasch and IRT Models: Overview

A simplified view, on how Rasch and IRT relate is shown in the tree below. Note that, the specialist of the field themselves do not totally agree on the similarity and boundaries between some of the models.

All Rasch models have in common that the item discrimination or the slope of the item characteristic curve (ICC), is a fix parameter which does not vary across items.

The ICC, item characteristic curve shows the response probability for a given ability \(\theta\) (here from 0 to 14). The item difficulty is set to \(\beta = 4, 6, 8, 10\). However, while the Rasch item discrimination is stable, i.e. \(a_i = 1\), the IRT model allows them to vary, here taking values of \(a_i = 0.25, 0.45, 0.75, 1\).

In the Rasch perspective: the raw score has all the information about the “ability” of the respondent = score sufficiency.

In the IRT perspective: the pattern of responses has all the information about the “ability” of the respondent.

Rasch Models

Rasch Model (RM) for dichotomous responses needs only two parameters to describe performance on the latent trait: the item difficulty (\(\beta\)) and the person ability (\(\theta\)).

Rating Scale Model (RSM) from (Andrich 2011) includes additionally a threshold parameter (\(\lambda\)) to calibrate assessment instruments with polytomous response options. The thresholds are set to be equidistant across items with identical number of response options.

Partial Credit Model (PCM) from (Masters 1982) is an extension of the RSM where thresholds are not forced to be equidistant and items can have different number of response options.

IRT Models

The IRT models start with the Rasch parameterisation and include additional parameters.

1-Parameter Logistic Model (1-PL) is similar to the Rasch model as it has only one parameter to estimate the model: the item difficulty

2-Parameter Logistic Models (2-PL) are an extension of the 1-PL model as it allows the items to have different item discrimination. Contrary to the Rasch models and the 1-PL model, persons with same item score can have different ability estimates, e.g. when one of the persons (with same score) has responded correctly to more difficult items.

3-Parameter Logistic (3-PL) is a further extension where a guession parameter is added to the model.

4-Parameter Logistic (4-PL) a further extension which accommodates for carelessness mistakes in high ability respondents.

Family of Rasch/IRT Models: Equations

‘Logic’ of Rasch models through Equations

Dichotomous Rasch Model

\[P(X_{ij} =1 | \theta_j) = \frac{exp(\theta_j - \beta_i)} {1 + exp(\theta_j - \beta_i)}\]

Ratings Scale Model (RSM) Andrich (1978)

RSM model is a Rasch model for polytomous response options. Threshold parameter can be split into location and response threshold (shift) :

\[\beta_{ik} = \beta_i + \lambda_k\]

The shift in difficulty when responding category \(k=2\) or \(k=1\), is equal to \(\beta_{i2} - \beta_{i1}\) for all the items of the scale. In fact, the item difficulties (\(\beta\)) can vary but not deviations (\(\lambda\)) for the response options (\(k\)), which are the same across the items. The probability of a response becomes:

\[P(X_{ikj}=1 | \theta_j) = \frac{exp{(\theta_j - \beta_{ik})}} {\Sigma^{m_i}_{c=0} exp \Sigma_{h=0}^{c} (\theta_j - \beta_{ik})}\]

Partial Credit Model (PCM) Masters (1982)

The PCM is also a Rasch model for polytomous response options. The equation is very similar to the RSM equation. However, \(\beta_{ik}\) the threshold parameter consists of the item location (\(\beta_i\)) and an item specific response category deviation parameter (\(\lambda_{ik}\)).

\[\beta_{ik} = \beta_i + \lambda_{ik}\] \(X_{ikj}\) is the \(j^{th}\) person’s response in category \(k\), with \(m_i + 1\) possible options, to the \(i^{th}\) item. Its probability is expressed with:

\[P(X_{ikj} = k | \theta_j) = \frac{exp{(\theta_j - \beta_{ik})}} {\Sigma^{m_i}_{c=0} exp \Sigma_{h=0}^{c} (\theta_j - \beta_{ik})}\]

‘Logic’ of IRT models through Equations

One-Parameter Logistic Model (1-PL)

1-PL is a special case of the 2-PL model with the slope parameter constrained to be the same across items. Despite striking similarities, it is often not considered identical to the Rasch model.

\[P(X_{ij} = 1 | \theta_j) = \frac{exp [a(\theta_j - \beta_{i})]} {1 + exp[a(\theta_j - \beta_{i})]}\]

Two-Parameter Logistic Model (2-PL)

2-PL is an extension of the 1-PL with an additional parameter a for the discrimination of the \(i^{th}\) item.

  • Graded Response Model (GRM) (Samejima 1969)

The GRM is a widely known IRT model. The GRM uses a cumulative category response function and has one additional parameter, \(a_i\), corresponding to the \(i^{th}\) item slope, so called discrimination parameter.

\[P(X_{ij} = 1 | \theta_j) = \frac{exp [a_i(\theta_j - \beta_{i})]} {1 + exp[a_i(\theta_j - \beta_{i})]}\]

  • Generalized Partial Credit Model (GPCM) (Muraki 1992)

The GPCM is an extension of the PCM model (and so also of the RSM) with itemwise unconstrained slope parameter, i.e. with an additional parameter for the item discrimination \(a_i\). It uses a score category response function to estimate the probability of a response \(X_{ijk}\) and is formalized as:

\[P(X_{ikj}= k | \theta_j) = \frac{exp \Sigma_{h=0}^k a_i(\theta_j - \beta_{ik})} { \Sigma^{m_i}_{c=0} exp \Sigma_{h=0}^{c}[a_i(\theta_j - \beta_{ik})]}\]

or parameterized with location (\(\beta\)) plus deviation (\(\lambda\)):

\[P(X_{ikj} = k | \theta_j) = \frac{exp \Sigma_{h=0}^k a_i(\theta_j - \beta_{i} + \lambda_{ik})} {\Sigma^{m_i}_{c=0} exp \Sigma_{h=0}^{c}[a_i(\theta_j - \beta_{i} + \lambda_{ik})]}\]

Three-Parameter Logistic Model (3-PL) (Birnbaum 1968)

The 3-PL adds a third parameter to the 2-PL model. The letter \(g\) represents parameter for response guessing. Under this model, persons with zero ability have still a chance of endorsing an item, by guessing randomly. How much guessing is expected can vary from item to item and is formalized as:

\[P(X_{ij} = 1 | \theta_j) = g_i + (1-g_i) \frac{exp[ a_i(\theta_j - \beta_{i})]} {1 + exp[a_i(\theta_j - \beta_i)]}\]

Four-Parameter Logistic Model (4-PL) (Barton and Lord 1981)

The 4-PL model adds a “slip” parameter, or upper asymptote, designed to accommodate high ability respondent’s carelessness mistakes and is formalized as follows:

\[P(X_{ij} = 1 | \theta_j) = g_i + (u_i - g_i) \frac{exp[ a_i(\theta_j - \beta_{i})]} {1 + exp[a_i(\theta_j - \beta_i)]}\]

The notation is similar to the 3-PL model, with the addition of the parameter \(u_i\).

Rasch Analysis in Practice

Rasch analysis is frequently applied to test if an instrument shows important (psycho)metric properties.

  • Stochastic ordering (fit of data to model)
  • Monotonicity (ordering of response options)
  • No local response dependencies or LID (no significant correlations between items)
  • No differential item functioning or DIF (no sample subgroup effects)
  • Unidimensionality (one latent construct)

The Rasch assumptions are tested iteratively while the assessment instrument is adjusted stepwise until all breaches to the Rasch assumptions are fixed.

R Packages

This course will use following R-packages to perform the Rasch analyses.

Main focus of the course is on the testing of psychometric assumptions with the Rasch model with the package eRm from (Mair, Hatzinger, and Maier 2019), technical details and references regarding the package and the functions it contains are found in R when typing vignette("eRm").

The R-package mirt(Chalmers 2012) will be shown to illustrate multidimensional analyses.

The R-package psych (Revelle 2019) contains various functions to simulate different type of psychometric data.

The R packages iarm (Mueller 2020) contains useful function for Rasch analysis.

Dichotomous Rasch Analysis

The most basic Rasch model is the model for dichotomously rated items.

# call the eRm library
library(eRm)
# simulate 10 dichotomous items for 500 persons
Data_Dicho <- sim.rasch(500, 10, seed = 1234)

RM_Dicho <- RM(Data_Dicho)

# note that the item difficulty (we are interested in, symbolized with beta in
# the equations) are named eta parameter in this package.  Beta stands here for
# the easiness parameter (the reverse of the difficulty).

summary(RM_Dicho)

Polytomous Rasch Analysis

Two models from the ‘Rasch family’ can deal with polytomous response options: the rating scale model (RSM) and the partial credit model (PCM).

The RSM assumes equidistant difficulty thresholds across items, the PCM does not constrain the difficulty thresholds.

First, we simulate polytomous data.

library(psych)  #package for data simulation

## function for gpcm but with always same constraint on slopes for Rasch simulates
## 8 items and 500 observations


## threshold simulation
set.seed(9876)  # reproducibility
Data_Poly <- sim.poly.npl(nvar = 8, n = 500, low = -4, high = 4, a = rep(1, 8), mu = 0, 
    sd = 1.96, cat = 3)$items

Rating Scale Model

RSM_Poly <- RSM(as.data.frame(Data_Poly))

Model comparison

The RSM is the less complex model using less parameter for estimation. It is generally recommended to test first if the data may fit this model instead of the PCM, if all items are polytomous with the same number of response options.

One way to compare the RSM and PCM model is to apply a statistical test to determine which equation fits best to the data. A well-known statistical test procedure for the comparison of nested models is the likelihood ratio test. Nested means that one model equation is more constrained (RSM) or nested in the less constrained model (PCM). Here, the nested models are also called the reduced (RSM) and the full (PCM) model. The likelihood ratio test is conducted using the anova() function, entering first the reduced than the full model.

The anova tests the null hypothesis that the RSM fits the data better, the alternative hypothesis that the PCM, the full model has a better fit. If the p-value is significant, i.e. \(< 0.05\), the null hypothesis can be rejected, meaning that there is a significant improvement in model fit when using the PCM.

Which model would we chose here?

anova(RSM_Poly, PCM_Poly)
## Analysis of Deviances Table
## 
## Model 1: PCM(X = Data_Poly)
## Model 2: RSM(X = as.data.frame(Data_Poly))
## 
##         cond. LL Deviance npar     LR df p-value
## Model 1  -1154.9   2309.8   15                  
## Model 2  -1160.3   2320.6    8 5.3921  7  0.6122

Exercise

Create a random sample of polytomous data with item discrimination constraint, for N = 500 persons and 15 items with 4 response categories, with difficulties ranging from -6 to 6 and with the spread of the latent variable set to 2.5 using sim.poly.npl.

Test which Rasch model fits the data better.

Please use set.seed(2020)for the random sampling and make sure that the results are invariant.
